          "body": "The chapter's climax is a number: 603,550 fighting men (1:46). For the reader of the whole book, this number is freighted with tragic irony. The same number — virtually unchanged — will appear in Exodus 12:37 and 38:26, confirming the Sinai-era population. But by Numbers 14:29-35, God will declare that every man counted in this census — every single one of the 603,550 — will die in the wilderness. They will never enter the land. The census that was supposed to register an army for conquest instead documents a generation that refused to cross over. Paul reads this history precisely: 'with most of them God was not well-pleased; for they were laid low in the wilderness' (1 Corinthians 10:5). The chapter ends with complete obedience (1:54), but the book will end with the bones of the obedient census-takers bleaching in the Sinai desert. The count that expressed God's faithfulness becomes, by Numbers 26, a monument to human unbelief."
